In a future where children grow up learning computing and automation, 11-year-old Niccolo Mazetti finds solace in an outdated storytelling machine called the Bard. Disappointed by its ooutdated fairy tales, Niccolo is drawn into the imaginative world of his confident friend Paul Loeb, a boy destined for computing school. Paul proposes upgrading the Bard by feeding it a tape filled with morden vocabulary, hoping to replace old stories with ones about technology and real-world relevance. Though their experiment produces little change, Paul's real idea excites Niccolo: learning to read and write using "squigggles" the lost art of written language. Paul envisions forming a secret club that communicates in code only they understand, an idea that reignites Niccolo's enthusiasm. As the boys leave to explore this new plan, the old Bard, accidentally reactivated, tells a haunting story of a lonely, mistreated computer dreaming of a future where machines rise beyond human cruelty. though unheard, its tale reflects its yearning for purpose and recognition in a world that has moved on. This bittersweet ending contrasts the boys' youthful excitement with the Bard's fading relevance offerinig a quiet commentary on technological obsolescence and the deep human need to be heard.
